fAnthDisturb.comment: Anthropogenic flux of carbon as carbon dioxide into the atmosphere. That is, emissions influenced, caused, or created by human activity. Anthropogenic emission of carbon dioxide includes fossil fuel use, cement production, agricultural burning and sources associated with anthropogenic land use change, except forest regrowth.
fAnthDisturb.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation, Litter or Soil Pools into the Atmosphere Due to any Human Activity [kgC m-2 s-1]

fBNF.comment: The fixation (uptake of nitrogen gas directly from the atmosphere) of nitrogen due to biological processes.

fCLandToOcean.comment: leached carbon etc that goes into run off or river routing and finds its way into ocean should be reported here.
fCLandToOcean.long_name: Lateral Transfer of Carbon out of Grid Cell That Eventually Goes into Ocean

fDeforestToAtmos.comment: When land use change results in deforestation of natural vegetation (trees or grasslands) then natural biomass is removed. The treatment of deforested biomass differs significantly across models, but it should be straight-forward to compare deforested biomass across models.
fDeforestToAtmos.long_name: Deforested Biomass That Goes into Atmosphere as a Result of Anthropogenic Land-Use Change [kgC m-2 s-1]

fDeforestToProduct.comment: When land use change results in deforestation of natural vegetation (trees or grasslands) then natural biomass is removed. The treatment of deforested biomass differs significantly across models, but it should be straight-forward to compare deforested biomass across models.
fDeforestToProduct.long_name: Deforested Biomass That Goes into Product Pool as a Result of Anthropogenic Land-Use Change

fFire.comment: CO2 emissions (expressed as a carbon mass flux per unit area) from natural fires and human ignition fires as calculated by the fire module of the dynamic vegetation model, but excluding any CO2 flux from fire included in fLuc (CO2 Flux to Atmosphere from Land Use Change).
fFire.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from Fire Excluding Land-Use Change [kgC m-2 s-1]

fFireAll.comment: From all sources,  Including natural, anthropogenic and Land-use change. Only total fire emissions can be compared to observations.
fFireAll.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from Fire Including All Sources [kgC m-2 s-1]

fFireNat.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from Natural Fire [kgC m-2 s-1]

fGrazing.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area due to grazing on land
fGrazing.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Grazing on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

fHarvest.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area due to crop harvesting
fHarvest.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Crop Harvesting [kgC m-2 s-1]

fHarvestToAtmos.comment: any harvested carbon that is assumed to decompose immediately into the atmosphere is reported here
fHarvestToAtmos.long_name: Harvested Biomass That Goes Straight into Atmosphere as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

fHarvestToProduct.comment: be it food or wood harvest, any carbon that is subsequently stored is reported here
fHarvestToProduct.long_name: Harvested Biomass That Goes into Product Pool

fLitterFire.comment: Required for unambiguous separation of vegetation and soil + litter turnover times, since total fire flux draws from both sources
fLitterFire.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux from Litter, CWD or any non-Living Pool into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from All Fire [kgC m-2 s-1]

fLitterSoil.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area into soil from litter (dead plant material in or above the soil).
fLitterSoil.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Litter to Soil

fLuc.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area into atmosphere due to human changes to land (excluding forest regrowth) accounting possibly for different time-scales related to fate of the wood, for example.
fLuc.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Land-Use Change [kgC m-2 s-1]

fLulccAtmLut.comment: This annual mean flux refers to the transfer of carbon directly to the atmosphere due to any land-use or land-cover change activities.  Include carbon transferred due to deforestation or agricultural directly into atmosphere, and  emissions form anthropogenic pools into atmosphere
fLulccAtmLut.long_name: Carbon Transferred Directly to Atmosphere Due to any Land-Use or Land-Cover Change Activities [kgC m-2 s-1]

fLulccProductLut.comment: This annual mean flux refers to the transfer of carbon primarily through harvesting land use into anthropogenic product pools, e.g.,deforestation or wood harvesting from primary or secondary lands, food harvesting on croplands, harvesting (grazing) by animals on pastures.
fLulccProductLut.long_name: Carbon Harvested Due to Land-Use or Land-Cover Change Process That Enters Anthropogenic Product Pools on Tile

fLulccResidueLut.comment: This annual mean flux refers to the transfer of carbon into soil or litter pools due to any land use or land-cover change activities
fLulccResidueLut.long_name: Carbon Transferred to Soil or Litter Pools Due to Land-Use or Land-Cover Change Processes on Tile

fN2O.comment: Surface upward flux of nitrous oxide (N2O) from vegetation (any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass), litter (dead plant material in or above the soil), soil.

fNAnthDisturb.comment: will require some careful definition to make sure we capture everything - any human activity that releases nitrogen from land  instead of into product pool goes here. E.g. Deforestation fire, harvest assumed to decompose straight away, grazing...
fNAnthDisturb.long_name: Nitrogen Mass Flux out of Land Due to any Human Activity

fNLandToOcean.comment: leached nitrogen etc that goes into run off or river routing and finds its way into ocean should be reported here.
fNLandToOcean.long_name: Lateral Transfer of Nitrogen out of Grid Cell That Eventually Goes into Ocean

fNLitterSoil.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil.
fNLitterSoil.long_name: Total Nitrogen Mass Flux from Litter to Soil

fNOx.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'Upward' indicates a vector component which is positive when directed upward (negative downward). In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The phrase 'expressed_as' is used in the construction A_expressed_as_B, where B is a chemical constituent of A. It means that the quantity indicated by the standard name is calculated solely with respect to the B contained in A, neglecting all other chemical constituents of A. 'Nox' means a combination of two radical species containing nitrogen and oxygen NO+NO2. 'Vegetation' means any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil.

fNProduct.comment: When land use change results in deforestation of natural vegetation (trees or grasslands) then natural biomass is removed. The treatment of deforested biomass differs significantly across models, but it should be straight-forward to compare deforested biomass across models.
fNProduct.long_name: Deforested or Harvested Biomass as a Result of Anthropogenic Land-Use or Change

fNVegLitter.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil. 'Vegetation' means any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass.
fNVegLitter.long_name: Total Nitrogen Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter

fNVegSoil.comment: In some models part of nitrogen (e.g., root exudate) can go directly into the soil pool without entering litter.
fNVegSoil.long_name: Total Nitrogen Mass Flux from Vegetation Directly to Soil

fNdep.long_name: Dry and Wet Deposition of Reactive Nitrogen onto Land

fNfert.comment: Total Nitrogen added for cropland fertilisation (artificial and manure). Relative to total land area of a grid cell, not relative to agricultural area
fNfert.long_name: Total Nitrogen Added for Cropland Fertilisation (Artificial and Manure)

fNgas.comment: Total flux of Nitrogen from the land into the atmosphere.
fNgas.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost to the Atmosphere (Sum of NHx, NOx, N2O, N2)

fNgasFire.comment: Flux of Nitrogen from the land into the atmosphere due to fire
fNgasFire.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost to the Atmosphere (Including NHx, NOx, N2O, N2) from Fire

fNgasNonFire.comment: Flux of Nitrogen from the land into the atmosphere due to all processes other than fire
fNgasNonFire.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost to the Atmosphere (Including NHx, NOx, N2O, N2) from All Processes Except Fire

fNleach.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The specification of a physical process by the phrase 'due_to_' process means that the quantity named is a single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity named by omitting the phrase. 'Leaching' means the loss of water soluble chemical species from soil. Runoff is the liquid water which drains from land. If not specified, 'runoff' refers to the sum of surface runoff and subsurface drainage.
fNleach.long_name: Total Nitrogen Loss to Leaching or Runoff (Sum of Ammonium, Nitrite and Nitrate)

fNloss.comment: Not all models split losses into gaseous and leaching
fNloss.long_name: Total Nitrogen Lost (Including NHx, NOx, N2O, N2 and Leaching)

fNnetmin.comment: Loss of soil nitrogen through remineralization and immobilisation. Remineralization is the degradation of organic matter into inorganic forms of carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus and other micronutrients, which consumes oxygen and releases energy. Immobilisation of nitrogen refers to retention of nitrogen by micro-organisms under certain conditions, making it unavailable for plants.
fNnetmin.long_name: Net Nitrogen Release from Soil and Litter as the Outcome of Nitrogen Immobilisation and Gross Mineralisation

fNup.comment: The uptake of nitrogen by fixation: nitrogen fixation means the uptake of nitrogen gas directly from the atmosphere.
fNup.long_name: Total Plant Nitrogen Uptake (Sum of Ammonium and Nitrate) Irrespective of the Source of Nitrogen

fProductDecomp.comment: Flux of CO2 from product pools into the atmosphere. Examples of 'forestry and agricultural products' are paper, cardboard, furniture, timber for construction, biofuels and food for both humans and livestock. Models that simulate land use changes have one or more pools of carbon that represent these products in order to conserve carbon and allow its eventual release into the atmosphere, for example, when the products decompose in landfill sites.
fProductDecomp.long_name: Decomposition out of Product Pools to CO2 in Atmosphere as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

fProductDecompLut.comment: Flux of CO2 from product pools into the atmosphere. Examples of 'forestry and agricultural products' are paper, cardboard, furniture, timber for construction, biofuels and food for both humans and livestock. Models that simulate land use changes have one or more pools of carbon that represent these products in order to conserve carbon and allow its eventual release into the atmosphere, for example, when the products decompose in landfill sites. Produce this variable i  a model has explicit anthropogenic product pools by land use tile
fProductDecompLut.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux from Wood and Agricultural Product Pools on Land Use Tile into Atmosphere [kgC m-2 s-1]

fVegFire.comment: Required for unambiguous separation of vegetation and soil + litter turnover times, since total fire flux draws from both sources
fVegFire.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation into Atmosphere Due to CO2 Emission from All Fire [kgC m-2 s-1]

fVegLitter.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. 'Vegetation' means any living plants e.g. trees, shrubs, grass. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil. It is distinct from coarse wood debris. The precise distinction between 'fine' and 'coarse' is model dependent. The sum of the quantities with standard names mass_flux_of_carbon_into_litter_from_vegetation_due_to_mortality and mass_flux_of_carbon_into_litter_from_vegetation_due_to_senescence is mass_flux_of_carbon_into_litter_from_vegetation.
fVegLitter.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter

fVegLitterMortality.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegLitterMortality.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter as a Result of Mortality

fVegLitterSenescence.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegLitterSenescence.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Litter as a Result of Leaf, Branch, and Root Senescence

fVegSoil.comment: Carbon mass flux per unit area from vegetation directly into soil, without intermediate conversion to litter.
fVegSoil.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation Directly to Soil

fVegSoilMortality.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegSoilMortality.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Soil as a Result of Mortality

fVegSoilSenescence.comment: needed to separate changing vegetation C turnover times resulting from changing allocation versus changing mortality
fVegSoilSenescence.long_name: Total Carbon Mass Flux from Vegetation to Soil as a Result of Leaf, Branch, and Root Senescence

fahLut.comment: Anthropogenic heat flux generated from non-renewable human primary energy consumption, including energy use by vehicles, commercial and residential buildings, industry, and power plants.  Primary energy refers to energy in natural resources, fossil and nonfossil, before conversion into other forms, such as electricity.
fahLut.long_name: Anthropogenic Heat Flux Generated from non-Renewable Human Primary Energy Consumption

fbddtalk.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of alkalinity
fbddtalk.long_name: Rate of Change of Biological Alkalinity Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdic.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of dissolved inorganic carbon
fbddtdic.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Carbon Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdife.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of dissolved inorganic iron
fbddtdife.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Iron Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdin.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of nitrogen nutrients (e.g. NO3+NH4)
fbddtdin.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Nitrogen Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdip.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of phosphate
fbddtdip.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Phosphorus Due to Biological Activity

fbddtdisi.comment: vertical integral of net biological terms in time rate of change of dissolved inorganic silicate
fbddtdisi.long_name: Rate of Change of Dissolved Inorganic Silicon Due to Biological Activity

fco2antt.comment: This is requested only for the emission-driven coupled carbon climate model runs.  Does not include natural fire sources but, includes all anthropogenic sources, including fossil fuel use, cement production, agricultural burning, and sources associated with anthropogenic land use change excluding forest regrowth.
fco2antt.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to All Anthropogenic Emissions of CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fco2fos.comment: This is the prescribed anthropogenic CO2 flux from fossil fuel use, including cement production, and flaring (but not from land-use changes, agricultural burning, forest regrowth, etc.)
fco2fos.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux into Atmosphere Due to Fossil Fuel Emissions of CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fco2nat.comment: This is what the atmosphere sees (on its own grid).  This field should be equivalent to the combined natural fluxes of carbon  that account for natural exchanges between the atmosphere and land (nep) or ocean (fgco2) reservoirs.
fco2nat.long_name: Surface Carbon Mass Flux into the Atmosphere Due to Natural Sources [kgC m-2 s-1]

fddtalk.comment: vertical integral of net time rate of change of alkalinity
fddtalk.long_name: Rate of Change of Total Alkalinity

fddtdic.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.  'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time. 'Dissolved inorganic carbon' describes a family of chemical species in solution, including carbon dioxide, carbonic acid and the carbonate and bicarbonate anions. 'Dissolved inorganic carbon' is the term used in standard names for all species belonging to the family that are represented within a given model. The list of individual species that are included in a quantity having a group chemical standard name can vary between models.  Where possible, the data variable should be accompanied by a complete description of the species represented, for example, by using a comment attribute.
fddtdic.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Carbon

fddtdife.comment: vertical integral of net time rate of change of dissolved inorganic iron
fddtdife.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Iron

fddtdin.comment: Net time rate of change of nitrogen nutrients (e.g. NO3+NH4)
fddtdin.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Nitrogen

fddtdip.comment: vertical integral of net  time rate of change of phosphate
fddtdip.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Phosphorus

fddtdisi.comment: vertical integral of net time rate of change of dissolved inorganic silicate
fddtdisi.long_name: Rate of Change of Net Dissolved Inorganic Silicon

fediss.comment: Dissolution, remineralization and desorption of iron back to the dissolved phase

fescav.comment: Dissolved Fe removed through nonbiogenic scavenging onto particles

fg13co2.comment: Gas exchange flux of carbon-13 as CO2 (positive into ocean)
fg13co2.long_name: Surface Downward Mass Flux of Carbon-13 as 13CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fg14co2.comment: Gas exchange flux of carbon-14 as CO2 (positive into ocean)
fg14co2.long_name: Surface Downward Mass Flux of Carbon-14 as 14CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fg14co2abio.comment: Gas exchange flux of abiotic 14CO2 (positive into ocean)
fg14co2abio.long_name: Surface Downward Mass Flux of Carbon-14 as Abiotic 14CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fgco2.comment: Gas exchange flux of CO2 (positive into ocean)
fgco2.long_name: Surface Downward Mass Flux of Carbon as CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fgco2abio.comment: Gas exchange flux of abiotic CO2 (positive into ocean)
fgco2abio.long_name: Surface Downward Mass Flux of Carbon as Abiotic CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fgco2nat.comment: Gas exchange flux of natural CO2 (positive into ocean)
fgco2nat.long_name: Surface Downward Mass Flux of Carbon as Natural CO2 [kgC m-2 s-1]

fgdms.comment: Gas exchange flux of DMS (positive into atmosphere)

fgo2.comment: Gas exchange flux of O2 (positive into ocean)

ficeberg.comment: computed as the iceberg melt water  flux into the ocean divided by the area of the ocean portion of the grid cell.
ficeberg.long_name: Water Flux into Sea Water from Icebergs

ficeberg2d.comment: computed as the iceberg melt water  flux into the ocean divided by the area of the ocean portion of the grid cell.
ficeberg2d.long_name: Water Flux into Sea Water from Icebergs

flandice.comment: Computed as the water flux into the ocean due to land ice (runoff water from surface and base of land ice or melt from base of ice shelf or vertical ice front) into the ocean divided by the area ocean portion of the grid cell
flandice.long_name: Water Flux into Sea Water from Land Ice

flashrate.comment: proposed name: lightning_flash_rate (units to be interpreted as 'counts km-2 s-1)

fldcapacity.comment: The field capacity of soil is the maximum content of water it can retain against gravitational drainage. Provide as a percentage of the soil volume.

fracInLut.comment: Cumulative percentage transitions over the year; note that percentage should be reported as a percentage of atmospheric grid cell
fracInLut.long_name: Annual Gross Percentage That Was Transferred into This Tile from Other Land-Use Tiles

fracLut.comment: End of year values (not annual mean); note that percentage should be reported as percentage of land grid cell (example: frac_lnd = 0.5, frac_ocn = 0.5, frac_crop_lnd = 0.2 (of land portion of grid cell), then frac_lut(crop) = 0.5*0.2 = 0.1)
fracLut.long_name: Percentage of Grid Cell for Each Land-Use Tile

fracOutLut.comment: Cumulative percentage transitions over the year; note that percentage should be reported as percentage of atmospheric grid cell
fracOutLut.long_name: Annual Gross Percentage of Land-Use Tile That Was Transferred into Other Land-Use Tiles

frfe.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.  The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a  single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity  named by omitting the phrase.  'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time.

fric.long_name: Downward Inorganic Carbon Flux at Ocean Bottom

friver.comment: computed as the river flux of water into the ocean divided by the area of the ocean portion of the grid cell.
friver.long_name: Water Flux into Sea Water from Rivers

frn.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.  The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity  named by omitting the phrase. 'Denitrification' is the conversion of nitrate into gaseous compounds such as nitric oxide, nitrous oxide and molecular nitrogen which are then emitted to the atmosphere.  'Sedimentation' is the sinking of particulate matter to the floor of a body of water. 'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time.
frn.long_name: Nitrogen Loss to Sediments and Through Denitrification

froc.long_name: Downward Organic Carbon Flux at Ocean Bottom

fsfe.comment: Iron supply through deposition flux onto sea surface, runoff, coasts, sediments, etc
fsfe.long_name: Surface Downward Net Flux of Iron

fsitherm.comment: computed as the sea ice thermodynamic water flux into the ocean divided by the area of the ocean portion of the grid cell.
fsitherm.long_name: Water Flux into Sea Water Due to Sea Ice Thermodynamics

fsn.comment: Flux of nitrogen into the ocean due to deposition (sum of dry and wet deposition), fixation (the production of ammonia from nitrogen gas by diazotrophs) and runoff (liquid water which drains from land).
fsn.long_name: Surface Downward Net Flux of Nitrogen

gpp.comment: The rate of synthesis of biomass from inorganic precursors by autotrophs ('producers') expressed as the mass of carbon which it contains. For example, photosynthesis in plants or phytoplankton. The producers also respire some of this biomass and the difference is referred to as the net primary production.
gpp.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux out of Atmosphere Due to Gross Primary Production on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

gppGrass.comment: Total GPP of grass in the grid cell
gppGrass.long_name: Gross Primary Production on Grass Tiles as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

gppLut.comment: The rate of synthesis of biomass from inorganic precursors by autotrophs ('producers') expressed as the mass of carbon which it contains. For example, photosynthesis in plants or phytoplankton. The producers also respire some of this biomass and the difference is referred to as the net primary production. Reported on land-use tiles.
gppLut.long_name: Gross Primary Production on Land-Use Tile as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

gppShrub.comment: Total GPP of shrubs in the grid cell
gppShrub.long_name: Gross Primary Production on Shrub Tiles as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

gppTree.comment: Total GPP of trees in the grid cell
gppTree.long_name: Gross Primary Production on Tree Tiles as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

gppc13.comment: The rate of synthesis of carbon-13 in biomass from inorganic precursors by autotrophs ('producers') expressed as the mass of carbon which it contains. For example, photosynthesis in plants or phytoplankton. The producers also respire some of this biomass and the difference is referred to as the net primary production.
gppc13.long_name: Carbon-13 Mass Flux out of Atmosphere Due to Gross Primary Production on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

gppc14.comment: The rate of synthesis of carbon-14 in biomass from inorganic precursors by autotrophs ('producers') expressed as the mass of carbon which it contains. For example, photosynthesis in plants or phytoplankton. The producers also respire some of this biomass and the difference is referred to as the net primary production.
gppc14.long_name: Carbon-14 Mass Flux out of Atmosphere Due to Gross Primary Production on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

grassFrac.comment: Percentage of entire grid cell that is covered by natural grass.

grassFracC3.comment: Percentage of entire grid cell covered by C3 natural grass.

grassFracC4.comment: Percentage of entire grid cell covered by C4 natural grass.

graz.comment: Total grazing of phytoplankton by zooplankton defined as tendency of moles of carbon per cubic metre.
graz.long_name: Total Grazing of Phytoplankton by Zooplankton

grpllsprof.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. Stratiform precipitation, whether liquid or frozen, is precipitation that formed in stratiform cloud. Graupel consists of heavily rimed snow particles, often called snow pellets; often indistinguishable from very small soft hail except when the size convention that hail must have a diameter greater than 5 mm is adopted. Reference: American Meteorological Society Glossary http://glossary.ametsoc.org/wiki/Graupel. There are also separate standard names for hail. Standard names for 'graupel_and_hail' should be used to describe data produced by models that do not distinguish between hail and graupel.

hcfc22global.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.  A chemical species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. The chemical formula for HCFC22 is CHClF2.  The IUPAC name for HCFC22 is chloro-difluoro-methane.
hcfc22global.long_name: Global Mean Mole Fraction of HCFC22

hcho.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

hcl.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.  The chemical formula of hydrogen chloride is HCl.

hfbasin.comment: Contains contributions from all physical processes affecting the northward heat transport, including resolved advection, parameterized advection, lateral diffusion, etc. Diagnosed here as a function of latitude and basin.   Use Celsius for temperature scale.

hfbasinpadv.comment: Contributions to heat transport from parameterized eddy-induced advective transport due to any subgrid advective process. Diagnosed here as a function of latitude and basin.  Use Celsius for temperature scale.
hfbasinpadv.long_name: Northward Ocean Heat Transport Due to Parameterized Eddy Advection

hfbasinpmadv.comment: Contributions to heat transport from parameterized mesoscale eddy-induced advective transport. Diagnosed here as a function of latitude and basin.  Use Celsius for temperature scale.
hfbasinpmadv.long_name: Northward Ocean Heat Transport Due to Parameterized Mesoscale Advection

hfbasinpmdiff.comment: Contributions to heat transport from parameterized mesoscale eddy-induced diffusive transport (i.e., neutral diffusion). Diagnosed here as a function of latitude and basin.
hfbasinpmdiff.long_name: Northward Ocean Heat Transport Due to Parameterized Mesoscale Diffusion

hfbasinpsmadv.comment: Contributions to heat transport from parameterized mesoscale eddy-induced advective transport. Diagnosed here as a function of latitude and basin.  Use Celsius for temperature scale.
hfbasinpsmadv.long_name: Northward Ocean Heat Transport Due to Parameterized Submesoscale Advection

hfcorr.comment: Flux correction is also called 'flux adjustment'. A positive flux correction is downward i.e. added to the ocean. In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics.

hfds.comment: This is the net flux of heat entering the liquid water column through its upper surface (excluding any 'flux adjustment') .
hfds.long_name: Downward Heat Flux at Sea Water Surface

hfdsl.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'Downward' indicates a vector component which is positive when directed downward (negative upward). The vertical heat flux in air is the sum of all heat fluxes i.e. radiative, latent and sensible. In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics.
hfdsl.long_name: Downward Heat Flux at Land Surface

hfdsn.comment: the net downward heat flux from the atmosphere into the snow that lies on land divided by the land area in the grid cell; reported as 0.0 for snow-free land regions or where the land fraction is 0.
hfdsn.long_name: Downward Heat Flux into Snow Where Land over Land

hfdsnb.comment: Heat flux from snow into the ice or land under the snow.
hfdsnb.long_name: Downward Heat Flux at Snow Base

hfevapds.comment: This is defined as 'where ice_free_sea over sea'
hfevapds.long_name: Temperature Flux Due to Evaporation Expressed as Heat Flux out of Sea Water

hfgeou.comment: Upward geothermal heat flux per unit area on the sea floor
hfgeou.long_name: Upward Geothermal Heat Flux at Sea Floor

hfgeoubed.comment: Upward geothermal heat flux per unit area into the base of grounded land ice. This is related to the geothermal heat flux out of the bedrock, but may be modified by horizontal transport due to run-off and by melting at the interface.
hfgeoubed.long_name: Geothermal Heat Flux Beneath Land Ice

iareagr.comment: Total area of the grounded ice sheets (the component of ice sheet resting over bedrock)
iareagr.long_name: Area Covered by Grounded Ice Sheet

icfriver.long_name: Flux of Inorganic Carbon into Ocean Surface by Runoff

intppdiat.comment: Vertically integrated primary (organic carbon) production by the diatom phytoplankton component alone

intppdiaz.comment: Vertically integrated primary (organic carbon) production by the diazotrophs alone
intppdiaz.long_name: Net Primary Mole Productivity of Carbon by Diazotrophs

intppmisc.comment: Vertically integrated total primary (organic carbon) production by other phytoplankton components alone
intppmisc.long_name: Net Primary Organic Carbon Production by Other Phytoplankton

intppnitrate.comment: Vertically integrated primary (organic carbon) production by phytoplankton based on nitrate uptake alone

jpdftaureicemodis.comment: Joint probability distribution function, giving probability of cloud as a function of optical thickness and particle size, as measured by MODIS. For cloud ice particles.

ksat.comment: Hydraulic conductivity is the constant k in Darcy's Law q=-k grad h for fluid flow q (volume transport per unit area i.e. velocity) through a porous medium, where h is the hydraulic head (pressure expressed as an equivalent depth of water).

lai.comment: A ratio obtained by dividing the total upper leaf surface area of vegetation by the (horizontal) surface area of the land on which it grows.

laiLut.comment: A ratio obtained by dividing the total upper leaf surface area of vegetation by the (horizontal) surface area of the land on which it grows.
laiLut.long_name: Leaf Area Index on Land-Use Tile

landCoverFrac.comment: Percentage of grid cell area occupied by different model vegetation/land cover categories. The categories may differ from model to model, depending on each model's subgrid land cover category definitions. Categories may include natural vegetation, anthropogenic vegetation, bare soil, lakes, urban areas, glaciers, etc. Sum of all should equal the percentage of the grid cell that is land.
landCoverFrac.long_name: Percentage of Area by Vegetation or Land-Cover Category

libmassbffl.comment: Specific mass balance means the net rate at which ice is added per unit area at the land ice base.  A negative value means loss of ice. Computed as the total basal mass balance on the floating land ice (floating ice shelf) portion of the grid cell divided by floating land ice (floating ice shelf) area in the grid cell. Cell_methods: area: mean where floating_ice_shelf
libmassbffl.long_name: Basal Specific Mass Balance Flux of Floating Ice Shelf

libmassbfgr.comment: Specific mass balance means the net rate at which ice is added per unit area at the land ice base.  A negative value means loss of ice. Computed as the total basal mass balance on the grounded land ice portion of the grid cell divided by grounded land ice area in the grid cell. Cell_methods: area: mean where grounded_ice_sheet
libmassbfgr.long_name: Basal Specific Mass Balance Flux of Grounded Ice Sheet

licalvf.comment: Loss of ice mass resulting from iceberg calving. Computed as the rate of mass loss by the ice shelf (in kg s-1) divided by the horizontal area of the ice sheet (m2) in the grid box.

lifmassbf.comment: Total mass balance at the ice front (or vertical margin). It includes both iceberg calving and melt on vertical ice front

lim.comment: The ice sheet mass is computed as the volume times density

Phytoplankton are algae that grow where there is sufficient light to support photosynthesis. 'Iron growth limitation' means the ratio of the growth rate of a species population in the environment (where there is a finite availability of iron) to the theoretical growth rate if there were no such limit on iron availability.

lwp.comment: The total mass of liquid water in cloud per unit area.

lwsffluxaero.comment: downwelling longwave  flux  due to volcanic aerosols at the surface to be diagnosed through double radiation call
lwsffluxaero.long_name: Longwave Flux Due to Volcanic Aerosols at the Surface

lwsnl.comment: The total mass of liquid water contained interstitially within the whole depth of the snow layer of the land portion of a grid cell divided by the area of the land portion of the cell.
lwsnl.long_name: Liquid Water Content of Snow Layer

lwsrfasdust.comment: The direct radiative effect refers to the instantaneous radiative impact on the Earth's energy balance, excluding secondary effects such as changes in cloud cover.
lwsrfasdust.long_name: All-Sky Surface Longwave Radiative Flux Due to Dust

lwsrfcsdust.comment: The direct radiative effect refers to the instantaneous radiative impact on the Earth's energy balance, excluding secondary effects such as changes in cloud cover. Calculating in clear-sky conditions.
lwsrfcsdust.long_name: Clear-Sky Surface Longwave Radiative Flux Due to Dust

lwtoaasdust.comment: Instantaneous forcing is the radiative flux change caused instantaneously by an imposed change in radiative forcing agent (greenhouse gases, aerosol, solar radiation, etc.).
lwtoaasdust.long_name: TOA All-Sky Longwave Radiative Forcing Due to Dust

lwtoacsaer.comment: Instantaneous forcing is the radiative flux change caused instantaneously by an imposed change in radiative forcing agent (greenhouse gases, aerosol, solar radiation, etc.).
lwtoacsaer.long_name: TOA Clear-Sky Longwave Radiative Forcing Due to Aerosols

lwtoacsdust.comment: The direct radiative effect refers to the instantaneous radiative impact on the Earth's energy balance, excluding secondary effects such as changes in cloud cover.
lwtoacsdust.long_name: TOA Clear-Sky Longwave Radiative Forcing Due to Dust

lwtoafluxaerocs.comment: downwelling longwave flux due to volcanic aerosols at TOA under clear sky to be diagnosed through double radiation call
lwtoafluxaerocs.long_name: TOA Outgoing Clear-Sky Longwave Flux Due to Volcanic Aerosols

masscello.comment: Tracer grid-cell mass per unit area used for computing tracer budgets. For Boussinesq models with static ocean grid cell thickness, masscello = rhozero*thickcello, where thickcello is static cell thickness and rhozero is constant Boussinesq reference density. More generally, masscello is time dependent and reported as part of Omon.

masso.comment: Total mass of liquid sea water. For Boussinesq models, report this diagnostic as Boussinesq reference density times total volume.

maxpblz.comment: maximum boundary layer height during the day (add cell_methods attribute: 'time: maximum')

mc.comment: The net mass flux should represent the difference between the updraft and downdraft components.  The flux is computed as the mass divided by the area of the grid cell.

mcd.comment: Calculated as the convective mass flux divided by the area of the whole grid cell (not just the area of the cloud).

mcu.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The atmosphere convective mass flux is the vertical transport of mass for a field of cumulus clouds or thermals, given by the product of air density and vertical velocity. For an area-average, cell_methods should specify whether the average is over all the area or the area of updrafts only.

md.comment: Emission from a primary source located anywhere within the atmosphere, including at the lower boundary (i.e. the surface of the earth).

meanage.comment: The mean age of air is defined as the mean time that a stratospheric air mass has been out of contact with the well-mixed troposphere.

mfo.comment: Transport across_line means that which crosses a particular line on the Earth's surface; formally this means the integral along the line of the normal component of the transport.

minpblz.comment: minimum boundary layer height during the day (add cell_methods attribute: 'time: minimum')

mlotst.comment: Sigma T is potential density referenced to ocean surface.
mlotst.long_name: Ocean Mixed Layer Thickness Defined by Sigma T

mlotstmax.comment: Sigma T is potential density referenced to ocean surface.
mlotstmax.long_name: Maximum Ocean Mixed Layer Thickness Defined by Sigma T

mlotstmin.comment: Sigma T is potential density referenced to ocean surface.
mlotstmin.long_name: Minimum Ocean Mixed Layer Thickness Defined by Sigma T

mlotstsq.comment: The phrase 'square_of_X' means X*X. The ocean mixed layer is the upper part of the ocean, regarded as being well-mixed. The base of the mixed layer defined by 'temperature', 'sigma', 'sigma_theta', 'sigma_t' or vertical diffusivity is the level at which the quantity indicated differs from its surface value by a certain amount. A coordinate variable or scalar coordinate variable with standard name sea_water_sigma_t_difference can be used to specify the sigma_t criterion that determines the layer thickness. Sigma-t of sea water is the density of water at atmospheric pressure (i.e. the surface) having the same temperature and salinity, minus 1000 kg m-3. 'Thickness' means the vertical extent of a layer.
mlotstsq.long_name: Square of Ocean Mixed Layer Thickness Defined by Sigma T

mmraerh2o.comment: Mass fraction is used in the construction mass_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y. It means the ratio of the mass of X to the mass of Y (including X). 'Aerosol' means the system of suspended liquid or solid particles in air (except cloud droplets) and their carrier gas, the air itself. 'Ambient_aerosol' means that the aerosol is measured or modelled at the ambient state of pressure, temperature and relative humidity that exists in its immediate environment. 'Ambient aerosol particles' are aerosol particles that have taken up ambient water through hygroscopic growth. The extent of hygroscopic growth depends on the relative humidity and the composition of the particles.

mmrbc.comment: Dry mass fraction of black carbon aerosol particles in air.

mmrdust.comment: Dry mass fraction of dust aerosol particles in air.

mmrnh4.comment: Dry mass fraction of ammonium aerosol particles in air.

mmrno3.comment: Dry mass fraction of nitrate aerosol particles in air.

mmroa.comment: We recommend a scale factor of POM=1.4*OC, unless your model has more detailed info available.
mmroa.long_name: Total Organic Aerosol Mass Mixing Ratio

mmrpm1.comment: Mass fraction atmospheric particulate compounds with an aerodynamic diameter of less than or equal to 1 micrometers

mmrpm10.comment: Mass fraction atmospheric particulate compounds with an aerodynamic diameter of less than or equal to 10 micrometers

mmrpm2p5.comment: Mass fraction atmospheric particulate compounds with an aerodynamic diameter of less than or equal to 2.5 micrometers

mmrso4.comment: Dry mass of sulfate (SO4) in aerosol particles as a fraction of air mass.

mmrsoa.comment: Mass fraction in the atmosphere of secondary organic aerosols (particulate organic matter formed within the atmosphere from gaseous precursors; dry mass).
mmrsoa.long_name: Secondary Organic Aerosol Mass Mixing Ratio

mmrss.comment: Mass fraction in the atmosphere of sea salt aerosol (dry mass).

modelCellAreai.comment: Horizontal area of ice-sheet grid cells
modelCellAreai.long_name: The Cell Area of the Ice Sheet Model

mrfso.comment: The mass per unit area (summed over all model layers) of frozen water.

mrfsofr.comment: Fraction of soil moisture mass in the solid phase in each user-defined soil layer (3D variable)
mrfsofr.long_name: Average Layer Fraction of Frozen Moisture

mrlqso.comment: Fraction of soil moisture mass in the liquid phase in each user-defined soil layer (3D variable)
mrlqso.long_name: Average Layer Fraction of Liquid Moisture

mrlso.comment: The mass (summed over all all layers) of liquid water.

mrro.comment: The total run-off (including drainage through the base of the soil model) per unit area leaving the land portion of the grid cell.

mrroIs.comment: The total run-off (including drainage through the base of the soil model) per unit area leaving the land portion of the grid cell.

mrroLi.comment: Runoff flux over land ice is the difference between any available liquid water in the snowpack less any refreezing. Computed as the sum of rainfall and melt of snow or ice less any refreezing or water retained in the snowpack

mrroLut.comment: the total runoff (including 'drainage' through the base of the soil model) leaving the land use tile portion of the grid cell

mrrob.comment: Runoff is the liquid water which drains from land. If not specified, 'runoff' refers to the sum of surface runoff and subsurface drainage. In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics.

mrros.comment: The total surface run off leaving the land portion of the grid cell (excluding drainage through the base of the soil model).

mrsfl.comment: in each soil layer, the mass of water in ice phase.  Reported as 'missing' for grid cells occupied entirely by 'sea'
mrsfl.long_name: Frozen Water Content of Soil Layer

mrsll.comment: in each soil layer, the mass of water in liquid phase.  Reported as 'missing' for grid cells occupied entirely by 'sea'
mrsll.long_name: Liquid Water Content of Soil Layer

mrso.comment: the mass per unit area  (summed over all soil layers) of water in all phases.

mrsoLut.comment: 'Water' means water in all phases. 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. The mass content of water in soil refers to the vertical integral from the surface down to the bottom of the soil model. For the content between specified levels in the soil, standard names including 'content_of_soil_layer' are used.

mrsofc.comment: The bulk water content retained by the soil at -33 J/kg of suction pressure, expressed as mass per unit land area; report as missing where there is no land
mrsofc.long_name: Capacity of Soil to Store Water (Field Capacity)

mrsol.comment: in each soil layer, the mass of water in all phases, including ice.  Reported as 'missing' for grid cells occupied entirely by 'sea'
mrsol.long_name: Total Water Content of Soil Layer

mrsos.comment: The mass of water in all phases in the upper 10cm of the  soil layer.
mrsos.long_name: Moisture in Upper Portion of Soil Column

mrsosLut.comment: the mass of water in all phases in a thin surface layer; integrate over uppermost 10cm
mrsosLut.long_name: Moisture in Upper Portion of Soil Column of Land-Use Tile

mrsow.comment: Vertically integrated soil moisture divided by maximum allowable soil moisture above wilting point.

mrtws.comment: Mass of water in all phases and in all components including soil, canopy, vegetation, ice sheets, rivers and ground water.

msftbarot.comment: Streamfunction or its approximation for free surface models. See OMDP document for details.

msftmrho.comment: Overturning mass streamfunction arising from all advective mass transport processes, resolved and parameterized.

msftmrhompa.comment: CMIP5 called this 'due to Bolus Advection'.  Name change respects the more general physics of the mesoscale parameterizations.
msftmrhompa.long_name: Ocean Meridional Overturning Mass Streamfunction Due to Parameterized Mesoscale Advection

msftmz.comment: Overturning mass streamfunction arising from all advective mass transport processes, resolved and parameterized.

msftmzmpa.comment: CMIP5 called this 'due to Bolus Advection'.  Name change respects the more general physics of the mesoscale parameterizations.
msftmzmpa.long_name: Ocean Meridional Overturning Mass Streamfunction Due to Parameterized Mesoscale Advection

msftmzsmpa.comment: Report only if there is a submesoscale eddy parameterization.
msftmzsmpa.long_name: Ocean Meridional Overturning Mass Streamfunction Due to Parameterized Submesoscale Advection

msftyrho.comment: Overturning mass streamfunction arising from all advective mass transport processes, resolved and parameterized.

msftyrhompa.comment: CMIP5 called this 'due to Bolus Advection'.  Name change respects the more general physics of the mesoscale parameterizations.
msftyrhompa.long_name: Ocean Y Overturning Mass Streamfunction Due to Parameterized Mesoscale Advection

msftyz.comment: Overturning mass streamfunction arising from all advective mass transport processes, resolved and parameterized.

msftyzmpa.comment: CMIP5 called this 'due to Bolus Advection'.  Name change respects the more general physics of the mesoscale parameterizations.
msftyzmpa.long_name: Ocean Y Overturning Mass Streamfunction Due to Parameterized Mesoscale Advection

msftyzsmpa.comment: Report only if there is a submesoscale eddy parameterization.
msftyzsmpa.long_name: Ocean Y Overturning Mass Streamfunction Due to Parameterized Submesoscale Advection

n2o.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.   The chemical formula of  nitrous oxide is N2O.

n2oClim.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.   The chemical formula of  nitrous oxide is N2O.

n2oglobal.long_name: Global Mean Mole Fraction of N2O

n2oglobalClim.long_name: Global Mean Mole Fraction of N2O

nLand.comment: Report missing data over ocean grid cells. For fractional land report value averaged over the land fraction.
nLand.long_name: Total Nitrogen in All Terrestrial Nitrogen Pools

nLeaf.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.

nLitter.comment: Report missing data over ocean grid cells. For fractional land report value averaged over the land fraction.

nLitterCwd.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. 'Wood debris' means dead organic matter composed of coarse wood. It is distinct from fine litter. The precise distinction between 'fine' and 'coarse' is model dependent. The sum of the quantities with standard names wood_debris_mass_content_of_nitrogen, surface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen is the total nitrogen mass content of dead plant material.
nLitterCwd.long_name: Nitrogen Mass in Coarse Woody Debris

nLitterSubSurf.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil. It is distinct from coarse wood debris. The precise distinction between 'fine' and 'coarse' is model dependent. 'Subsurface litter' means the part of the litter mixed within the soil below the surface. The sum of the quantities with standard names wood_debris_mass_content_of_nitrogen, surface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen is the total nitrogen mass content of dead plant material.
nLitterSubSurf.long_name: Nitrogen Mass in Below-Ground Litter (non CWD)

nLitterSurf.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. 'Litter' is dead plant material in or above the soil. It is distinct from coarse wood debris. The precise distinction between 'fine' and 'coarse' is model dependent. 'Surface litter' means the part of the litter resting above the soil surface. The sum of the quantities with standard names wood_debris_mass_content_of_nitrogen, surface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen and subsurface_litter_mass_content_of_nitrogen is the total nitrogen mass content of dead plant material.
nLitterSurf.long_name: Nitrogen Mass in Above-Ground Litter (non CWD)

nMineral.comment: SUM of ammonium, nitrite, nitrate, etc over all soil layers

nMineralNH4.comment: SUM of ammonium over all soil layers

nMineralNO3.comment: SUM of nitrate over all soil layers

nOther.long_name: Nitrogen Mass in Vegetation Components Other than Leaves, Stem and Root

nProduct.comment: Report missing data over ocean grid cells. For fractional land report value averaged over the land fraction.
nProduct.long_name: Nitrogen Mass in Products of Land-Use Change

nSoil.comment: Report missing data over ocean grid cells. For fractional land report value averaged over the land fraction.

nVeg.comment: Report missing data over ocean grid cells. For fractional land report value averaged over the land fraction.

nbp.comment: This is the net mass flux of carbon from atmosphere into land, calculated as photosynthesis MINUS the sum of  plant and soil respiration, carbon fluxes from fire, harvest, grazing  and land use change. Positive flux is into the land.
nbp.long_name: Carbon Mass Flux out of Atmosphere Due to Net Biospheric Production on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

necbLut.comment: Computed as npp minus heterotrophic respiration minus fire minus C leaching minus harvesting/clearing. Positive rate is into the land, negative rate is from the land.  Do not include fluxes from anthropogenic product pools to atmosphere
necbLut.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux into Land-Use Tile [kgC m-2 s-1]

nep.comment: Natural flux of CO2 (expressed as a mass flux of carbon) from the atmosphere to the land calculated as the difference between uptake associated will photosynthesis and the release of CO2 from the sum of plant and soil respiration and fire.  Positive flux is into the land.  Emissions from natural fires and human ignition fires as calculated by the fire module of the dynamic vegetation model, but excluding any CO2 flux from fire included in fLuc (CO2 Flux to Atmosphere from Land Use Change).
nep.long_name: Net Carbon Mass Flux out of Atmosphere Due to Net Ecosystem Productivity on Land [kgC m-2 s-1]

netAtmosLandC13Flux.comment: Flux of carbon 31as carbon dioxide into the land. This flux should be reproducible by differencing the sum of all carbon pools (cVeg, cLitter, cSoil, and cProducts or equivalently cLand) from one time step to the next, except in the case of lateral transfer of carbon due to harvest, riverine transport of dissolved organic and/or inorganic carbon, or any other process (in which case the lateral_carbon_transfer_over_land term, see below, will be zero data).-
netAtmosLandC13Flux.long_name: Net Mass Flux of 13C Between Atmosphere and Land (Positive into Land) as a Result of All Processes [kgC m-2 s-1]

netAtmosLandC14Flux.comment: Flux of carbon-14 as carbon dioxide into the land. This flux should be reproducible by differencing the sum of all carbon pools (cVeg, cLitter, cSoil, and cProducts or equivalently cLand) from one time step to the next, except in the case of lateral transfer of carbon due to harvest, riverine transport of dissolved organic and/or inorganic carbon, or any other process (in which case the lateral_carbon_transfer_over_land term, see below, will be zero data).
netAtmosLandC14Flux.long_name: Net Mass Flux of 14C Between Atmosphere and Land (Positive into Land) as a Result of All Processes [kgC m-2 s-1]

netAtmosLandCO2Flux.comment: Flux of carbon as carbon dioxide into the land. This flux should be reproducible by differencing the sum of all carbon pools (cVeg, cLitter, cSoil, and cProducts or equivalently cLand) from one time step to the next, except in the case of lateral transfer of carbon due to harvest, riverine transport of dissolved organic and/or inorganic carbon, or any other process (in which case the lateral_carbon_transfer_over_land term, see below, will be zero data).
netAtmosLandCO2Flux.long_name: Net Flux of CO2 Between Atmosphere and Land (Positive into Land) as a Result of All Processes [kgC m-2 s-1]

nh4.comment: Mole concentration means moles (amount of substance) per unit volume and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

nh4os.comment: Mole concentration means moles (amount of substance) per unit volume and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

nh50.comment: Fixed surface layer mixing ratio over 30o-50oN (100ppbv), uniform fixed 50-day exponential decay.

no.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

no2.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

no3.comment: Mole concentration means moles (amount of substance) per unit volume and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

no3os.comment: Mole concentration means moles (amount of substance) per unit volume and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

noy.comment: Total family (the sum of all appropriate species in the model); list the species in the netCDF header, e.g. NOy = N + NO + NO2 + NO3 + HNO3 + 2N2O5 + HNO4 + ClONO2 + BrONO2 Definition: Total reactive nitrogen; usually includes atomic nitrogen (N), nitric oxide (NO), NO2, nitrogen trioxide (NO3), dinitrogen radical (N2O5), nitric acid (HNO3), peroxynitric acid (HNO4), BrONO2, ClONO2 add comment attribute with detailed description about how the model calculates these fields
noy.long_name: Total Reactive Nitrogen Volume Mixing Ratio

npp.comment: 'Production of carbon' means the production of biomass expressed as the mass of carbon which it contains. Net primary production is the excess of gross primary production (rate of synthesis of biomass from inorganic precursors) by autotrophs ('producers'), for example, photosynthesis in plants or phytoplankton, over the rate at which the autotrophs themselves respire some of this biomass. 'Productivity' means production per unit area. The phrase 'expressed_as' is used in the construction A_expressed_as_B, where B is a chemical constituent of A. It means that the quantity indicated by the standard name is calculated solely with respect to the B contained in A, neglecting all other chemical constituents of A.
npp.long_name: Net Primary Production on Land as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppGrass.comment: Total NPP of grass in the grid cell
nppGrass.long_name: Net Primary Production on Grass Tiles as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppLeaf.comment: This is the rate of carbon uptake by leaves due to NPP
nppLeaf.long_name: Net Primary Production Allocated to Leaves as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppLut.comment: 'Production of carbon' means the production of biomass expressed as the mass of carbon which it contains. Net primary production is the excess of gross primary production (rate of synthesis of biomass from inorganic precursors) by autotrophs ('producers'), for example, photosynthesis in plants or phytoplankton, over the rate at which the autotrophs themselves respire some of this biomass. 'Productivity' means production per unit area. The phrase 'expressed_as' is used in the construction A_expressed_as_B, where B is a chemical constituent of A. It means that the quantity indicated by the standard name is calculated solely with respect to the B contained in A, neglecting all other chemical constituents of A.
nppLut.long_name: Net Primary Production on Land-Use Tile as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppOther.long_name: Net Primary Production Allocated to Other Pools (not Leaves Stem or Roots) as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppRoot.comment: This is the rate of carbon uptake by roots due to NPP
nppRoot.long_name: Net Primary Production Allocated to Roots as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppShrub.comment: Total NPP of shrubs in the grid cell
nppShrub.long_name: Net Primary Production on Shrub Tiles as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppStem.long_name: Net Primary Production Allocated to Stem as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppTree.comment: Total NPP of trees in the grid cell
nppTree.long_name: Net Primary Production on Tree Tiles as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nppWood.comment: This is the rate of carbon uptake by wood due to NPP
nppWood.long_name: Net Primary Production Allocated to Wood as Carbon Mass Flux [kgC m-2 s-1]

nudgincsm.comment: A nudging increment refers to an amount added to parts of a model system. The phrase 'nudging_increment_in_X' refers to an increment in quantity X over a time period which should be defined in the bounds of the time coordinate. 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. 'Water' means water in all phases. The mass content of water in soil refers to the vertical integral from the surface down to the bottom of the soil model. The 'soil content' of a quantity refers to the vertical integral from the surface down to the bottom of the soil model. For the content between specified levels in the soil, standard names including 'content_of_soil_layer' are used.
nudgincsm.long_name: Nudging Increment of Water in Soil Moisture

nudgincswe.comment: A nudging increment refers to an amount added to parts of a model system. The phrase 'nudging_increment_in_X' refers to an increment in quantity X over a time period which should be defined in the bounds of the time coordinate. The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'Amount' means mass per unit area. 'Snow and ice on land' means ice in glaciers, ice caps, ice sheets & shelves, river and lake ice, any other ice on a land surface, such as frozen flood water, and snow lying on such ice or on the land surface.
nudgincswe.long_name: Nudging Increment of Water in Snow

nwdFracLut.comment: Percentage of land use tile tile that is non-woody vegetation ( e.g. herbaceous crops)

o2.comment: 'Mole concentration' means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.  A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'.

o2min.comment: 'Mole concentration' means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.  A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. The concentration of any chemical species, whether particulate or dissolved, may vary with depth in the ocean.  A depth profile may go through one or more local minima in concentration. The mole_concentration_of_molecular_oxygen_in_sea_water_at_shallowest_local_minimum_in_vertical_profile is the mole concentration of oxygen at the local minimum in the concentration profile that occurs closest to the sea surface.

o2os.comment: 'Mole concentration' means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.  A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'.

o2sat.comment: 'Mole concentration at saturation' means the mole concentration in a saturated solution. Mole concentration means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction 'mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y', where X is a material constituent of Y. A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'.

o2satos.comment: 'Mole concentration at saturation' means the mole concentration in a saturated solution. Mole concentration means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction 'mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y', where X is a material constituent of Y. A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'.
o2satos.long_name: Surface Dissolved Oxygen Concentration at Saturation

o3.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

o3Clim.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

o3loss.comment: ONLY provide the sum of the following reactions: (i) O(1D)+H2O; (ii) O3+HO2; (iii) O3+OH; (iv) O3+alkenes (isoprene, ethene,...)

o3prod.comment: ONLY provide the sum of all the HO2/RO2 + NO reactions (as k*[HO2]*[NO])

o3ste.comment: Ozone tracer intended to map out strat-trop exchange (STE) of ozone. Set to ozone in the stratosphere, then destroyed in the troposphere using the ozone chemical loss rate. Please specify the tropopause definition used
o3ste.long_name: Stratospheric Ozone Tracer Volume Mixing Ratio

obvfsq.comment: The phrase 'square_of_X' means X*X. Frequency is the number of oscillations of a wave per unit time. Brunt-Vaisala frequency is also sometimes called 'buoyancy frequency' and is a measure of the vertical stratification of the medium.
obvfsq.long_name: Square of Brunt Vaisala Frequency in Sea Water

ocfriver.comment: Organic Carbon supply to ocean through runoff (separate from gas exchange)
ocfriver.long_name: Flux of Organic Carbon into Ocean Surface by Runoff

ocontempdiff.comment: Tendency of heat content for a grid cell from parameterized dianeutral mixing. Reported only for models that use conservative temperature as prognostic field.
ocontempdiff.long_name: Tendency of Sea Water Conservative Temperature Expressed as Heat Content Due to Parameterized Dianeutral Mixing

ocontempmint.comment: Full column sum of density*cell thickness*conservative temperature. If the model is Boussinesq, then use Boussinesq reference density for the density factor.
ocontempmint.long_name: Depth Integral of Product of Sea Water Density and Conservative Temperature

ocontemppadvect.comment: Tendency of heat content for a grid cell from parameterized eddy advection (any form of eddy advection). Reported only for models that use conservative temperature as prognostic field.
ocontemppadvect.long_name: Tendency of Sea Water Conservative Temperature Expressed as Heat Content Due to Parameterized Eddy Advection

ocontemppmdiff.comment: Tendency of heat content for a grid cell from parameterized mesoscale eddy diffusion. Reported only for models that use conservative temperature as prognostic field.
ocontemppmdiff.long_name: Tendency of Sea Water Conservative Temperature Expressed as Heat Content Due to Parameterized Mesoscale Diffusion

ocontemppsmadvect.comment: Tendency of heat content for a grid cell from parameterized submesoscale eddy advection. Reported only for models that use conservative temperature as prognostic field.

ocontemprmadvect.comment: Conservative Temperature is defined as part of the Thermodynamic Equation of Seawater 2010 (TEOS-10) which was adopted in 2010 by the International Oceanographic Commission (IOC). The phrase 'residual mean advection' refers to the sum of the model's resolved advective transport plus any parameterized advective transport. Parameterized advective transport includes processes such as parameterized mesoscale and submesoscale transport, as well as any other advectively parameterized transport. When the parameterized advective transport is represented in the model as a skew-diffusion rather than an advection, then the parameterized skew diffusion should be included in this diagnostic, since the convergence of skew-fluxes are identical (in the continuous formulation) to the convergence of advective fluxes.

pathetao.comment: The quantity with standard name sea_water_added_potential_temperature is a passive tracer in an ocean model whose surface flux does not come from the atmosphere but is imposed externally upon the simulated climate system. The surface flux is expressed as a heat flux and converted to a passive tracer increment as if it were a heat flux being added to potential temperature. The passive tracer is transported within the ocean as if it were potential temperature. The passive tracer is zero in the control climate of the model. The passive tracer records added heat, as described for the CMIP6 FAFMIP experiment (doi:10.5194/gmd-9-3993-2016), following earlier ideas. Potential temperature is the temperature a parcel of air or sea water would have if moved adiabatically to sea level pressure.

This is the value from uppermost model layer with liquid cloud or, if available, or for some models it is the sum over all liquid cloud tops, no matter where they occur, as long as they are seen from the top of the atmosphere (TOA) each time sample when computing monthly mean. Reported values are weighted by total liquid cloud top fraction of  (as seen from TOA) each time sample when computing monthly mean.

reffgrpls.comment: This is defined as the in-cloud ratio of the third moment over the second moment of the particle size distribution (obtained by considering only the cloudy portion of the grid cell).

reffrainc.comment: This is defined as the in-cloud ratio of the third moment over the second moment of the particle size distribution (obtained by considering only the cloudy portion of the grid cell).

rhc13.comment: Heterotrophic respiration is respiration by heterotrophs ('consumers'), which are organisms (including animals and decomposers) that consume other organisms or dead organic material, rather than synthesising organic material from inorganic precursors using energy from the environment (especially sunlight) as autotrophs ('producers') do. Heterotrophic respiration goes on within both the soil and litter pools.

rlds.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'longwave' means longwave radiation. Downwelling radiation is radiation from above. It does not mean 'net downward'. When thought of as being incident on a surface, a radiative flux is sometimes called 'irradiance'. In addition, it is identical with the quantity measured by a cosine-collector light-meter and sometimes called 'vector irradiance'. In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics.
