rtmt.long_name: Net Downward Radiative Flux at Top of Model

rv850.comment: Relative vorticity is the upward component of the vorticity vector i.e. the component which arises from horizontal velocity.

rzwc.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area. The content of a soil layer is the vertical integral of the specified quantity within the layer. The quantity with standard name mass_content_of_water_in_soil_layer_defined_by_root_depth is the vertical integral between the surface and the depth to which plant roots penetrate. A coordinate variable or scalar coordinate variable with standard name root_depth can be used to specify the extent of the layer. 'Water' means water in all phases.

sandfrac.comment: 'Volume fraction' is used in the construction volume_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

sbl.comment: The snow and ice sublimation flux is the loss of snow and ice mass per unit area from the surface resulting from their direct conversion to water vapor that enters the atmosphere.
sbl.long_name: Surface Snow and Ice Sublimation Flux

sblIs.comment: The snow and ice sublimation flux is the loss of snow and ice mass per unit area from the surface resulting from their direct conversion to water vapor that enters the atmosphere.
sblIs.long_name: Ice Sheet Surface Snow and Ice Sublimation Flux

sblnosn.comment: Rate of sublimation of ice into the atmosphere from areas with no snow.
sblnosn.long_name: Sublimation of the Snow Free Area

sci.comment: Fraction of time that shallow convection occurs in the grid cell.
sci.long_name: Fraction of Time Shallow Convection Occurs

scldncl.comment: Droplets are liquid only.  Report concentration 'as seen from space' over stratiform liquid cloudy portion of grid cell.  This is the value from uppermost model layer with liquid cloud or, if available, it is better to sum over all liquid cloud tops, no matter where they occur, as long as they are seen from the top of the atmosphere. Weight by total liquid cloud top fraction of  (as seen from TOA) each time sample when computing monthly mean.
scldncl.long_name: Cloud Droplet Number Concentration of Stratiform Cloud Tops

sconcdust.comment: mass concentration of dust dry aerosol in air in model lowest layer

sconcso4.comment: mass concentration of sulfate dry aerosol in air in model lowest layer.

sconcss.comment: mass concentration of sea-salt dry aerosol in air in model lowest layer

sedustCI.comment: Dry mass deposition rate of dust aerosol.
sedustCI.long_name: Sedimentation Flux of Dust Mode Coarse Insoluble

sf6.comment: Mole concentration means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction 'mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y', where X is a material constituent of Y. A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. The chemical formula of sulfur hexafluoride is SF6.
sf6.long_name: Mole Concentration of SF6 in Sea Water

sfcWindmax.comment: Daily maximum near-surface (usually, 10 meters) wind speed.

sfdsi.comment: This field is physical, and it arises since sea ice has a nonzero salt content, so it exchanges salt with the liquid ocean upon melting and freezing.
sfdsi.long_name: Downward Sea Ice Basal Salt Flux

sfno2.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.
sfno2.long_name: NO2 Volume Mixing Ratio in Lowest Model Layer

sfo3.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.
sfo3.long_name: O3 Volume Mixing Ratio in Lowest Model Layer

sfo3max.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.
sfo3max.long_name: Daily Maximum O3 Volume Mixing Ratio in Lowest Model Layer

sfpm25.comment: Mass fraction of atmospheric particulate compounds with an aerodynamic diameter of less than or equal to 2.5 micrometers. To specify the relative humidity and temperature at which the particle size applies, provide scalar coordinate variables with the standard names of 'relative_humidity' and 'air_temperature'.
sfpm25.long_name: PM2.5 Mass Mixing Ratio in Lowest Model Layer

sfriver.comment: This field is physical, and it arises when rivers carry a nonzero salt content.  Often this is zero, with rivers assumed to be fresh.
sfriver.long_name: Salt Flux into Sea Water from Rivers

sftflf.comment: Percentage of grid cell covered by floating ice shelf, the component of the ice sheet that is flowing over sea water

sftgif.comment: Percentage of grid cell covered by land ice (ice sheet, ice shelf, ice cap, glacier)

sftgrf.comment: Percentage of grid cell covered by grounded ice sheet

sftlf.comment: Percentage of horizontal area occupied by land.
sftlf.long_name: Percentage of the Grid Cell Occupied by Land (Including Lakes)

sftof.comment: Percentage of horizontal area occupied by ocean.

shrubFrac.comment: Percentage of entire grid cell  that is covered by shrub.

si.comment: Mole concentration means number of moles per unit volume, also called 'molarity', and is used in the construction 'mole_concentration_of_X_in_Y', where X is a material constituent of Y. A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. 'Dissolved inorganic silicon' means the sum of all inorganic silicon in solution (including silicic acid and its first dissociated anion SiO(OH)3-).

siareaacrossline.comment: net (sum of transport in all directions) sea ice area transport through the following four passages, positive into the Arctic Ocean 1. Fram Strait = (11.5W,81.3N to (10.5E,79.6N) 2. Canadian Archipelago = (128.2W,70.6N) to (59.3W,82.1N) 3. Barents opening = (16.8E,76.5N) to (19.2E,70.2N) 4. Bering Strait = (171W,66.2N) to (166W,65N)

siarean.comment: total area of sea ice in the Northern hemisphere

siareas.comment: total area of sea ice in the Southern hemisphere

sicompstren.comment: Computed strength of the ice pack, defined as the energy (J m-2) dissipated per unit area removed from the ice pack under compression, and assumed proportional to the change in potential energy caused by ridging. For Hibler-type models, this is P (= P*h exp(-C(1-A)) where P* is compressive strength, h ice thickness, A compactness and C strength reduction constant).

siconc.comment: Percentage of grid cell covered by sea ice

siconca.comment: Percentage of grid cell covered by sea ice

sidconcdyn.comment: Total change in sea-ice area fraction through dynamics-related processes (advection, divergence...)
sidconcdyn.long_name: Sea-Ice Area Percentage Tendency Due to Dynamics

sidconcth.comment: Total change in sea-ice area fraction through thermodynamic processes
sidconcth.long_name: Sea-Ice Area Percentage Tendency Due to Thermodynamics

sidivvel.comment: Divergence of sea-ice velocity field (first shear strain invariant)
sidivvel.long_name: Divergence of the Sea-Ice Velocity Field

sidmassdyn.comment: Total change in sea-ice mass through dynamics-related processes (advection,...) divided by grid-cell area

sidmassevapsubl.comment: The rate of change of sea-ice mass change through evaporation and sublimation divided by grid-cell area
sidmassevapsubl.long_name: Sea-Ice Mass Change Through Evaporation and Sublimation

sidmassgrowthbot.comment: The rate of change of sea ice mass due to vertical growth of existing sea ice at its base divided by grid-cell area.
sidmassgrowthbot.long_name: Sea-Ice Mass Change Through Basal Growth

sidmassgrowthwat.comment: The rate of change of sea ice mass due to sea ice formation in supercooled water (often through frazil formation) divided by grid-cell area. Together, sidmassgrowthwat and sidmassgrowthbot should give total ice growth
sidmassgrowthwat.long_name: Sea-Ice Mass Change Through Growth in Supercooled Open Water (Frazil)

sidmasslat.comment: The rate of change of sea ice mass through lateral melting divided by grid-cell area (report 0 if not explicitly calculated thermodynamically)

sidmassmeltbot.comment: The rate of change of sea ice mass through melting at the ice bottom divided by grid-cell area
sidmassmeltbot.long_name: Sea-Ice Mass Change Through Bottom Melting

sidmassmelttop.comment: The rate of change of sea ice mass through melting at the ice surface divided by grid-cell area
sidmassmelttop.long_name: Sea-Ice Mass Change Through Surface Melting

sidmasssi.comment: The rate of change of sea ice mass due to transformation of snow to sea ice divided by grid-cell area
sidmasssi.long_name: Sea-Ice Mass Change Through Snow-to-Ice Conversion

sidmassth.comment: Total change in sea-ice mass from thermodynamic processes divided by grid-cell area

sidmasstranx.comment: Includes transport of both sea ice and snow by advection

sidmasstrany.comment: Includes transport of both sea ice and snow by advection

sidragbot.comment: Oceanic drag coefficient that is used to calculate the oceanic momentum drag on sea ice

sidragtop.comment: Atmospheric drag coefficient that is used to calculate the atmospheric momentum drag on sea ice

siextentn.comment: Total area of all Northern-Hemisphere grid cells that are covered by at least 15 % areal fraction of sea ice

siextents.comment: Total area of all Southern-Hemisphere grid cells that are covered by at least 15 % areal fraction of sea ice

sifb.comment: Mean height of sea-ice surface (=snow-ice interface when snow covered) above sea level

siflcondbot.comment: the net heat conduction flux at the ice base
siflcondbot.long_name: Net Conductive Heat Fluxes in Ice at the Bottom

siflcondtop.comment: the net heat conduction flux at the ice surface
siflcondtop.long_name: Net Conductive Heat Flux in Ice at the Surface

siflfwbot.comment: Total flux of fresh water from water into sea ice divided by grid-cell area; This flux is negative during ice growth (liquid water mass decreases, hence upward flux of freshwater), positive during ice melt (liquid water mass increases, hence downward flux of freshwater)

siflfwdrain.comment: Total flux of fresh water from sea-ice surface into underlying ocean. This combines both surface melt water that drains directly into the ocean and the drainage of surface melt pond. By definition, this flux is always positive.

sifllatstop.comment: the net latent heat flux over sea ice
sifllatstop.long_name: Net Latent Heat Flux over Sea Ice

sifllwdtop.comment: the downwelling longwave flux over sea ice (always positive)
sifllwdtop.long_name: Downwelling Longwave Flux over Sea Ice

sifllwutop.comment: the upwelling longwave flux over sea ice (always negative)
sifllwutop.long_name: Upwelling Longwave Flux over Sea Ice

siflsenstop.comment: the net sensible heat flux over sea ice
siflsenstop.long_name: Net Upward Sensible Heat Flux over Sea Ice

siflsensupbot.comment: the net sensible heat flux under sea ice from the ocean
siflsensupbot.long_name: Net Upward Sensible Heat Flux Under Sea Ice

siflswdbot.comment: The downwelling shortwave flux underneath sea ice (always positive)
siflswdbot.long_name: Downwelling Shortwave Flux Under Sea Ice

siflswdtop.comment: The downwelling shortwave flux over sea ice (always positive by sign convention)
siflswdtop.long_name: Downwelling Shortwave Flux over Sea Ice

siflswutop.comment: The upwelling shortwave flux over sea ice (always negative)
siflswutop.long_name: Upwelling Shortwave Flux over Sea Ice

siforcecoriolx.comment: X-component of force on sea ice caused by coriolis force

siforcecorioly.comment: Y-component of force on sea ice caused by coriolis force

siforceintstrx.comment: X-component of force on sea ice caused by internal stress (divergence of sigma)

siforceintstry.comment: Y-component of force on sea ice caused by internal stress (divergence of sigma)

siforcetiltx.comment: X-component of force on sea ice caused by sea-surface tilt

siitdconc.comment: Percentage of grid cell covered by each ice-thickness category (vector with one entry for each thickness category starting from the thinnest category, netcdf file should use thickness bounds of the categories as third coordinate axis)
siitdconc.long_name: Sea-Ice Area Percentages in Thickness Categories

siitdsnconc.comment: Percentage of grid cell covered by snow in each ice-thickness category (vector with one entry for each thickness category starting from the thinnest category, netcdf file should use thickness bounds of the categories as third coordinate axis)

siitdsnthick.long_name: Snow Thickness in Ice Thickness Categories

siitdthick.comment: Actual (floe) thickness of sea ice in each  category (NOT volume divided by grid area),  (vector with one entry for each thickness category starting from the thinnest category, netcdf file should use thickness bounds of categories as third coordinate axis)

siltfrac.comment: Volume fraction of silt in soil

simass.comment: Total mass of sea ice divided by grid-cell area

simassacrossline.comment: net (sum of transport in all directions) sea ice area transport through the following four passages, positive into the Arctic Ocean 1. Fram Strait = (11.5W,81.3N to (10.5E,79.6N) 2. Canadian Archipelago = (128.2W,70.6N) to (59.3W,82.1N) 3. Barents opening = (16.8E,76.5N) to (19.2E,70.2N) 4. Bering Strait = (171W,66.2N) to (166W,65N)

simpconc.comment: Percentage of sea ice, by area, which is covered by melt ponds, giving equal weight to every square metre of sea ice .
simpconc.long_name: Percentage Cover of Sea Ice by Meltpond

simpmass.long_name: Meltpond Mass per Unit Area (as Depth)

simprefrozen.comment: Volume of refrozen ice on melt ponds divided by meltpond covered area
simprefrozen.long_name: Thickness of Refrozen Ice on Melt Pond

A chemical or biological species denoted by X may be described by a single term such as 'nitrogen' or a phrase such as 'nox_expressed_as_nitrogen'. 'Dissolved inorganic silicon' means the sum of all inorganic silicon in solution (including silicic acid and its first dissociated anion SiO(OH)3-).

sipr.comment: mass of liquid precipitation falling onto sea ice divided by grid-cell area

sirdgconc.comment: Fraction of sea ice, by area, which is covered by sea ice ridges, giving equal weight to every square metre of sea ice .
sirdgconc.long_name: Percentage Cover of Sea Ice by Ridging

sirdgthick.comment: Sea Ice Ridge Height (representing mean height over the ridged area)

sisali.comment: Mean sea-ice salinity of all sea ice in grid cell

sisaltmass.comment: Total mass of all salt in sea ice divided by grid-cell area
sisaltmass.long_name: Mass of Salt in Sea Ice per Area

sishevel.comment: Maximum shear of sea-ice velocity field (second shear strain invariant)
sishevel.long_name: Maximum Shear of Sea-Ice Velocity Field

sisnconc.comment: Percentage of sea ice, by area, which is covered by snow, giving equal weight to every square metre of sea ice . Exclude snow that lies on land or land ice.

sisnhc.comment: Heat-content of all snow in grid cell divided by total grid-cell area. Snow-water equivalent at 0 Celsius is assumed to have a heat content of 0 J.  Does not include heat content of sea ice.

sisnmass.comment: Total mass of snow on sea ice divided by sea-ice area.

sisnthick.comment: Actual thickness of snow (snow volume divided by snow-covered area)

sispeed.comment: Speed of ice (i.e. mean absolute velocity) to account for back-and-forth movement of the ice

sistremax.long_name: Maximum Shear Stress in Sea Ice

sistresave.comment: Average normal stress in sea ice (first stress invariant)
sistresave.long_name: Average Normal Stress in Sea Ice

sistrxdtop.comment: X-component of atmospheric stress on sea ice
sistrxdtop.long_name: X-Component of Atmospheric Stress on Sea Ice

sistrxubot.comment: X-component of ocean stress on sea ice
sistrxubot.long_name: X-Component of Ocean Stress on Sea Ice

sistrydtop.comment: Y-component of atmospheric stress on sea ice
sistrydtop.long_name: Y-Component of Atmospheric Stress on Sea Ice

sistryubot.comment: Y-component of ocean stress on sea ice
sistryubot.long_name: Y-Component of Ocean Stress on Sea Ice

siu.comment: The x-velocity of ice on native model grid

siv.comment: The y-velocity of ice on native model grid

sivoln.comment: total volume of sea ice in the Northern hemisphere

sivols.comment: total volume of sea ice in the Southern hemisphere

sltovgyre.comment: From all advective mass transport processes, resolved and parameterized.

sltovovrt.comment: From all advective mass transport processes, resolved and parameterized.

snc.comment: Percentage of each grid cell that is occupied by snow that rests on land portion of cell.

sncIs.comment: Percentage of each grid cell that is occupied by snow that rests on land portion of cell.

snd.comment: where land over land, this is computed as the mean thickness of snow in the land portion of the grid cell (averaging over the entire land portion, including the snow-free fraction).  Reported as 0.0 where the land fraction is 0.

sndmassdyn.comment: The rate of change of snow mass through advection with sea ice divided by sea-ice area
sndmassdyn.long_name: Snow Mass Rate of Change Through Advection by Sea-Ice Dynamics

sndmassmelt.comment: the rate of change of snow mass through melt divided by sea-ice area
sndmassmelt.long_name: Snow Mass Rate of Change Through Melt

sndmasssi.comment: the rate of change of snow mass due to transformation of snow to sea ice divided by sea-ice area
sndmasssi.long_name: Snow Mass Rate of Change Through Snow-to-Ice Conversion

sndmasssnf.comment: mass of solid precipitation falling onto sea ice divided by sea-ice area
sndmasssnf.long_name: Snow Mass Change Through Snow Fall

sndmasssubl.comment: the rate of change of snow mass through sublimation and evaporation divided by sea-ice area
sndmasssubl.long_name: Snow Mass Rate of Change Through Evaporation or Sublimation

sndmasswindrif.comment: the rate of change of snow mass through wind drift of snow (from sea-ice into the sea) divided by sea-ice area
sndmasswindrif.long_name: Snow Mass Rate of Change Through Wind Drift of Snow

snicefreezIs.comment: Mass flux of surface meltwater which refreezes within the snowpack. Computed as the total refreezing on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell.
snicefreezIs.long_name: Ice Sheet Surface Snow and Ice Refreeze Flux

snicem.comment: Loss of snow and ice mass resulting from surface melting. Computed as the total surface melt on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell.
snicem.long_name: Surface Snow and Ice Melt Flux

snicemIs.comment: Loss of snow and ice mass resulting from surface melting. Computed as the total surface melt on the land ice portion of the grid cell divided by land ice area in the grid cell.
snicemIs.long_name: Ice Sheet Surface Snow and Ice Melt Flux

snm.comment: The total surface snow melt rate on the land portion of the grid cell divided by the land area in the grid cell; report as zero for snow-free land regions and missing where there is no land.

snmIs.comment: The total surface snow melt rate on the land portion of the grid cell divided by the land area in the grid cell; report as zero for snow-free land regions and missing where there is no land.

snmsl.comment: Mass flow rate of water draining out of the snow pack.

snowmxrat27.long_name: Mass Fraction of Snow in Air

snrefr.comment: In accordance with common usage in geophysical disciplines, 'flux' implies per unit area, called 'flux density' in physics. The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'Surface snow and ice refreezing flux' means the mass flux of surface  meltwater which refreezes within the snow or firn.
snrefr.long_name: Refreezing of Water in the Snow

snw.comment: The mass of surface snow on the land portion of the grid cell divided by the land area in the grid cell; reported as missing where the land fraction is 0; excludes snow on vegetation canopy or on sea ice.

snwc.comment: Total water mass of the snowpack (liquid or frozen), averaged over a grid cell and intercepted by the canopy.
snwc.long_name: Snow Water Equivalent Intercepted by the Vegetation

so.comment: Sea water salinity is the salt content of sea water, often on the Practical Salinity Scale of 1978. However, the unqualified term 'salinity' is generic and does not necessarily imply any particular method of calculation. The units of salinity are dimensionless and the units attribute should normally be given as 1e-3 or 0.001 i.e. parts per thousand.

so2.comment: Mole fraction is used in the construction mole_fraction_of_X_in_Y, where X is a material constituent of Y.

sob.comment: Model prognostic salinity at bottom-most model grid cell
sob.long_name: Sea Water Salinity at Sea Floor

spco2.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. The partial pressure of a dissolved gas in sea water is the partial pressure in air with which it would be in equilibrium. The partial pressure of a gaseous constituent of air is the pressure which it alone would exert with unchanged temperature and number of moles per unit volume. The chemical formula for carbon dioxide is CO2.
spco2.long_name: Surface Aqueous Partial Pressure of CO2

spco2abio.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. The chemical formula for carbon dioxide is CO2. In ocean biogeochemistry models, an 'abiotic analogue' is used to simulate the effect on a modelled variable when biological effects on ocean carbon concentration and alkalinity are ignored. The partial pressure of a gaseous constituent of air is the pressure which it alone would exert with unchanged temperature and number of moles per unit volume. The partial pressure of a dissolved gas in sea water is the partial pressure in air with which it would be in equilibrium. The partial pressure difference between sea water and air is positive when the partial pressure of the dissolved gas in sea water is greater than the partial pressure in air.
spco2abio.long_name: Abiotic Surface Aqueous Partial Pressure of CO2

spco2nat.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. The chemical formula for carbon dioxide is CO2. In ocean biogeochemistry models, a 'natural analogue' is used to simulate the effect on a modelled variable of imposing preindustrial atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations, even when the model as a whole may be subjected to varying forcings. The partial pressure of a gaseous constituent of air is the pressure which it alone would exert with unchanged temperature and number of moles per unit volume. The partial pressure of a dissolved gas in sea water is the partial pressure in air with which it would be in equilibrium. The partial pressure difference between sea water and air is positive when the partial pressure of the dissolved gas in sea water is greater than the partial pressure in air.
spco2nat.long_name: Natural Surface Aqueous Partial Pressure of CO2

strbasemag.comment: Magnitude of basal drag at land ice base

sw.comment: Total liquid water storage, other than soil, snow or interception storage (i.e. lakes, river channel or depression storage).

sw17O.comment: Ratio of abundance of oxygen-17 (17O) atoms to oxygen-16 (16O) atoms in sea water
sw17O.long_name: Isotopic Ratio of Oxygen-17 in Sea Water

sw18O.comment: Ratio of abundance of oxygen-18 (18O) atoms to oxygen-16 (16O) atoms in sea water
sw18O.long_name: Isotopic Ratio of Oxygen-18 in Sea Water

sw2H.comment: Ratio of abundance of hydrogen-2 (2H) atoms to hydrogen-1 (1H) atoms in sea water
sw2H.long_name: Isotopic Ratio of Deuterium in Sea Water

sweLut.comment: The surface called 'surface' means the lower boundary of the atmosphere. 'lwe' means liquid water equivalent. 'Amount' means mass per unit area. The construction lwe_thickness_of_X_amount or _content means the vertical extent of a layer of liquid water having the same mass per unit area. Surface amount refers to the amount on the ground, excluding that on the plant or vegetation canopy.

swsffluxaero.comment: Shortwave heating rate due to volcanic aerosols to be diagnosed through double radiation call

swsrfasdust.comment: The direct radiative effect refers to the instantaneous radiative impact on the Earth's energy balance, excluding secondary effects such as changes in cloud cover.

swsrfcsdust.comment: The direct radiative effect refers to the instantaneous radiative impact on the Earth's energy balance, excluding secondary effects such as changes in cloud cover. Calculated in clear-sky conditions.
swsrfcsdust.long_name: Clear-Sky Surface Shortwave Radiative Flux Due to Dust

swtoaasdust.comment: Instantaneous forcing is the radiative flux change caused instantaneously by an imposed change in radiative forcing agent (greenhouse gases, aerosol, solar radiation, etc.).
swtoaasdust.long_name: All-Sky Shortwave Flux Due to Dust at Toa

swtoacsdust.comment: Instantaneous forcing is the radiative flux change caused instantaneously by an imposed change in radiative forcing agent (greenhouse gases, aerosol, solar radiation, etc.).
swtoacsdust.long_name: Clear Sky Shortwave Flux Due to Dust at Toa

swtoafluxaerocs.comment: Downwelling shortwave flux due to volcanic aerosols at TOA under clear sky to be diagnosed through double radiation call
swtoafluxaerocs.long_name: TOA Outgoing Clear-Sky Shortwave Flux Due to Volcanic Aerosols

sza.comment: The angle between the line of sight to the sun and the local vertical

t20d.comment: This quantity, sometimes called the 'isotherm depth', is the depth (if it exists) at which the sea water potential temperature equals some specified value. This value should be specified in a scalar coordinate variable. Depth is the vertical distance below the surface. Potential temperature is the temperature a parcel of air or sea water would have if moved adiabatically to sea level pressure.

tSoilPools.comment: defined as 1/(turnover time) for each soil pool. Use the same pools reported under cSoilPools
tSoilPools.long_name: Turnover Rate of Each Model Soil Carbon Pool

talk.comment: total alkalinity equivalent concentration (including carbonate, nitrogen, silicate, and borate components)

talknat.comment: total alkalinity equivalent concentration (including carbonate, borate, phosphorus, silicon, and nitrogen components) at preindustrial atmospheric xCO2

talknatos.comment: total alkalinity equivalent concentration (including carbonate, borate, phosphorus, silicon, and nitrogen components) at preindustrial atmospheric xCO2

talkos.comment: total alkalinity equivalent concentration (including carbonate, borate, phosphorus, silicon, and nitrogen components)

tasLut.comment: Air temperature is the bulk temperature of the air, not the surface (skin) temperature.
tasLut.long_name: Near-Surface Air Temperature on Land Use Tile

tasmaxCrop.comment: maximum near-surface (usually, 2 meter) air temperature (add cell_method attribute 'time: max')

tasmin.comment: minimum near-surface (usually, 2 meter) air temperature (add cell_method attribute 'time: min')

tasminCrop.comment: minimum near-surface (usually, 2 meter) air temperature (add cell_method attribute 'time: min')

tendlibmassbf.comment: The total basal mass balance flux over land ice is a spatial integration of the basal mass balance flux

tendlicalvf.comment: The total calving flux over land ice is a spatial integration of the calving flux

thetaoga.comment: Diagnostic should be contributed even for models using conservative temperature as prognostic field
thetaoga.long_name: Global Average Sea Water Potential Temperature

thetaot.comment: Vertical average of the sea water potential temperature through the whole ocean depth
thetaot.long_name: Vertically Averaged Sea Water Potential Temperature

thetaot2000.long_name: Depth Average Potential Temperature of Upper 2000m

thetaot300.long_name: Depth Average Potential Temperature of Upper 300m

thetaot700.long_name: Depth Average Potential Temperature of Upper 700m

tnhusa.comment: Tendency of Specific Humidity due to Advection
tnhusa.long_name: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Advection

tnhusc.long_name: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Convection

tnhusd.comment: Tendency of specific humidity due to numerical diffusion.This includes any horizontal or vertical numerical moisture diffusion not associated with the parametrized moist physics or the resolved dynamics.  For example, any vertical diffusion which is part of the boundary layer mixing scheme should be excluded, as should any diffusion which is included in the terms from the resolved dynamics.   This term is required to check the closure of the moisture budget.
tnhusd.long_name: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Numerical Diffusion

tnhusmp.comment: Tendency of specific humidity due to model physics. This includes sources and sinks from parametrized moist physics (e.g. convection, boundary layer, stratiform condensation/evaporation, etc.) and excludes sources and sinks from resolved dynamics or from horizontal or vertical numerical diffusion not associated with model physics.  For example any diffusive mixing by the boundary layer scheme would be included.
tnhusmp.long_name: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Model Physics

tnhuspbl.comment: Includes all boundary layer terms including diffusive terms.
tnhuspbl.long_name: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Boundary Layer Mixing

tnhusscp.comment: The phrase 'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time. 'Specific' means per unit mass. Specific humidity is the mass fraction of water vapor in (moist) air. The specification of a physical process by the phrase 'due_to_' process means that the quantity named is a single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity named by omitting the phrase. A variable with the standard name of tendency_of_specific_humidity_due_to_stratiform_cloud_and_precipitation should contain the effects of all processes which convert stratiform clouds and precipitation to or from water vapor. In an atmosphere model, stratiform cloud is that produced by large-scale convergence (not the convection schemes).
tnhusscp.long_name: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Stratiform Clouds and Precipitation

tnhusscpbl.comment: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Stratiform Cloud and Precipitation and Boundary Layer Mixing  (to be specified only in  models which do not separate budget terms for stratiform cloud, precipitation and boundary layer schemes.  Includes all boundary layer terms including and diffusive terms.)
tnhusscpbl.long_name: Tendency of Specific Humidity Due to Stratiform Cloud and Precipitation and Boundary Layer Mixing

tnkebto.comment: Depth integrated impacts on kinetic energy arising from parameterized eddy-induced advection. For CMIP5, this diagnostic was 3d, whereas the CMIP6 depth integrated diagnostic is sufficient for many purposes and reduces archive requirements.
tnkebto.long_name: Tendency of Ocean Eddy Kinetic Energy Content Due to Parameterized Eddy Advection

tnkebto2d.comment: Depth integrated impacts on kinetic energy arising from parameterized eddy-induced advection. For CMIP5, this diagnostic was 3d, whereas the CMIP6 depth integrated diagnostic is sufficient for many purposes and reduces archive requirements.
tnkebto2d.long_name: Tendency of Ocean Eddy Kinetic Energy Content Due to Parameterized Eddy Advection

tnpeo.comment: Rate that work is done against vertical stratification, as measured by the vertical heat and salt diffusivity. Report here as depth integrated two-dimensional field.
tnpeo.long_name: Tendency of Ocean Potential Energy Content

tnpeot.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.  Potential energy is the sum of the gravitational potential energy relative to the geoid and the centripetal potential energy. (The geopotential is the specific potential energy.)  'Due to tides' means due to all astronomical gravity changes which manifest as tides.  No distinction is made between different tidal components. The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a  single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity  named by omitting the phrase.  'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time.
tnpeot.long_name: Tendency of Ocean Potential Energy Content Due to Tides

tnpeotb.comment: 'Content' indicates a quantity per unit area.  Potential energy is the sum of the gravitational potential energy relative to the geoid and the centripetal potential energy. (The geopotential is the specific potential energy.)  'Due to background' means caused by a time invariant imposed field which may be either constant over the globe or spatially varying, depending on the ocean model used. The specification of a physical process by the phrase due_to_process means that the quantity named is a  single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity  named by omitting the phrase.  'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time.
tnpeotb.long_name: Tendency of Ocean Potential Energy Content Due to Background

tnta.long_name: Tendency of Air Temperature Due to Advection

tntc.long_name: Tendency of Air Temperature Due to Convection

For example, any vertical diffusion which is part of the boundary layer mixing scheme should be excluded, as should any diffusion which is included in the terms from the resolved dynamics.   This term is required to check the closure of the temperature budget.

tntmp.comment: Tendency of air temperature due to model physics. This includes sources and sinks from parametrized physics (e.g. radiation, convection, boundary layer, stratiform condensation/evaporation, etc.). It excludes sources and sinks from resolved dynamics and numerical diffusion not associated with parametrized physics.  For example, any vertical diffusion which is part of the boundary layer mixing scheme should be included, while numerical diffusion applied in addition to physics or resolved dynamics should be excluded.  This term is required to check the closure of the heat budget.
tntmp.long_name: Tendency of Air Temperature Due to Model Physics

tntmp27.comment: Tendency of air temperature due to model physics. This includes sources and sinks from parametrized physics (e.g. radiation, convection, boundary layer, stratiform condensation/evaporation, etc.). It excludes sources and sinks from resolved dynamics and numerical diffusion not associated with parametrized physics.  For example, any vertical diffusion which is part of the boundary layer mixing scheme should be included, while numerical diffusion applied in addition to physics or resolved dynamics should be excluded.  This term is required to check the closure of the heat budget.

tntscp.comment: The phrase 'tendency_of_X' means derivative of X with respect to time. Air temperature is the bulk temperature of the air, not the surface (skin) temperature. The specification of a physical process by the phrase 'due_to_' process means that the quantity named is a single term in a sum of terms which together compose the general quantity named by omitting the phrase. A variable with the standard name tendency_of_air_temperature_due_to_stratiform_cloud_and_precipitation should contain net latent heating effects of all processes which convert stratiform clouds and precipitation between water vapour, liquid or ice phases. In an atmosphere model, stratiform cloud is that produced by large-scale convergence (not the convection schemes).
tntscp.long_name: Tendency of Air Temperature Due to Stratiform Clouds and Precipitation

zfull.comment: Height of full model levels above a reference ellipsoid. A reference ellipsoid is a mathematical figure that approximates the geoid. The geoid is a surface of constant geopotential with which mean sea level would coincide if the ocean were at rest. The ellipsoid is an approximation because the geoid is an irregular shape. A number of reference ellipsoids are defined for use in the field of geodesy. To specify which reference ellipsoid is being used, a grid_mapping variable should be attached to the data variable as described in Chapter 5.6 of the CF Convention.

zfullo.long_name: Depth Below Geoid of Ocean Layer

zg.comment: Geopotential is the sum of the specific gravitational potential energy relative to the geoid and the specific centripetal potential energy. Geopotential height is the geopotential divided by the standard acceleration due to gravity. It is numerically similar to the altitude (or geometric height) and not to the quantity with standard name height, which is relative to the surface.
